  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Department of Defense contract obligations are $239B for FY2026 to date, with 2,048,079 awards and an average award size of $117K. Obligations are down 51.5% year over year, and current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date). Historical annual obligations show an increase through FY25 before the FY26 partial total: FY21 was $387B, FY22 was $414B, FY23 was $457B, FY24 was $446B, and FY25 was $492B. The FY26 to-date mix is concentrated in aircraft and aerospace-related manufacturing and engineering services, with Aircraft Manufacturing at $31.1B, Engineering Services at $22.8B, and Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $21.6B. Health-related obligations also appear among the largest categories, with Direct Health and Medical Insurance Carriers at $11.8B and major healthcare vendors appearing in the top vendor list. Top vendor names and amounts in FY2026 to date include multiple large defense primes and healthcare suppliers, led by LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $10B and another LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION entry at $8.8B.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How have overall obligations changed year over year?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 51.5% year over year for FY2026 to date. The FY26 partial total is $239B compared with prior full-year totals: FY25 $492B, FY24 $446B, FY23 $457B, FY22 $414B, and FY21 $387B. The government executed 2,048,079 awards in FY2026 to date with an average award size of $117K. Current-year totals are partial and reported fiscal year to date."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which categories and vendors account for the largest FY2026 to-date spending?",
        "body": "Top spending categories in FY2026 to date include Aircraft Manufacturing at $31.1B, Engineering Services at $22.8B, and Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $21.6B. Other large categories include Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences at $16.2B and Direct Health and Medical Insurance Carriers at $11.8B. Leading vendors in FY2026 to date include LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $10B and another LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION entry at $8.8B, followed by ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION at $8.3B and THE BOEING COMPANY at $5.8B."
      }
    ]
  },
  "faq": [
    {
      "q": "How much does Department of Defense spend on contracts?",
      "a": "Department of Defense has $239B in contract obligations in FY2026 to date. The agency executed 2,048,079 awards in that period with an average award size of $117K, and obligations are down 51.5% year over year. Historical full-year obligations were FY25 $492B, FY24 $446B, FY23 $457B, FY22 $414B, and FY21 $387B."
    },
    {
      "q": "What does Defense buy?",
      "a": "Defense buys a mix of aerospace, engineering, research, health, shipbuilding, and construction goods and services. Top FY2026 to-date NAICS categories are Aircraft Manufacturing $31.1B, Engineering Services $22.8B, Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing $21.6B, Research and Development in the Physical, Engineering, and Life Sciences $16.2B, and Direct Health and Medical Insurance Carriers $11.8B."
    },
    {
      "q": "Who are Defense's largest contractors?",
      "a": "Defense's largest contractors in FY2026 to date include LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $10B and a second LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION entry at $8.8B. Other top vendors are ELECTRIC BOAT CORPORATION $8.3B, THE BOEING COMPANY $5.8B and $4.3B (two entries), RAYTHEON COMPANY $4.8B, TRIWEST HEALTHCARE ALLIANCE CORP $4.6B, HUMANA GOVERNMENT BUSINESS INC $4.6B, AMERISOURCEBERGEN DRUG CORP $4.1B, and RTX CORPORATION $3B."
